# Hue and Cry

This article is about a common law term. For other uses, see [Hue and Cry (disambiguation)](/Hue_and_Cry_(disambiguation)).

In [common law](/Common_law), a hue and cry is a process by which bystanders are summoned to assist in the apprehension of a [criminal](/Crime) who has been witnessed in the act of committing a [crime](/Crime). This ancient legal concept, rooted in the collective responsibility of communities, represents one of the earliest forms of community policing and criminal pursuit. The hue and cry was not merely a call for help but a legally binding obligation that required all able-bodied men to join in the pursuit of a fleeing criminal, ensuring that justice was not just a matter for authorities but a communal duty.

## History

The origins of the hue and cry can be traced back to early medieval Europe, where it served as a fundamental aspect of maintaining law and order in societies that lacked formal police forces. The concept was formalized in England through the [Statute of Winchester](/Statute_of_Winchester) of 1285, which was enacted during the reign of [King Edward I](/Edward_I_of_England). This statute provided a comprehensive framework for the hue and cry, mandating that anyone who witnessed a crime was obligated to raise the alarm. The hue and cry was to be maintained from town to town and county to county until the criminal was apprehended and delivered to the sheriff. This system was not just a call for assistance but a legally enforceable duty, with severe consequences for those who failed to participate or who raised a false alarm.

### Hue and Cry Act 1734

The [Hue and Cry Act 1734](/Hue_and_Cry_Act_1734) was an Act of the [Parliament of Great Britain](/Parliament_of_Great_Britain) that aimed to amend the law relating to actions on the Statute of Hue and Cry. The long title of the Act was "An Act for the Amendment of the Law relating to Actions on the Statute of Hue and Cry." It received [Royal assent](/Royal_assent) on 15 May 1735 and came into force on 24 June 1735. The Act was repealed in [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) on 1 July 1827 and in [India](/India) on 1 March 1829. It amended the [Statute of Westminster 1285](/Statute_of_Westminster_1285) and the Hue and Cry Act 1584. The Act was repealed by the [Criminal Statutes Repeal Act 1827](/Criminal_Statutes_Repeal_Act_1827) in England and Wales and by the [Criminal Law (India) Act 1828](/Criminal_Law_(India)_Act_1828) in India. It is related to the [Statute of Winchester](/Statute_of_Winchester) and the [Hue and Cry Act 1748](/Hue_and_Cry_Act_1748).

### Hue and Cry Act 1748

The [Hue and Cry Act 1748](/Hue_and_Cry_Act_1748) was another Act of the [Parliament of Great Britain](/Parliament_of_Great_Britain) that aimed to remedy inconveniences that might arise from proceedings in actions on the Statutes of Hue and Cry. The long title of the Act was "An Act for remedying Inconveniencies which may happen by Proceedings in Actions on the Statutes of Hue and Cry." It received [Royal assent](/Royal_assent) on 26 May 1749 and came into force on 24 June 1749. The Act was repealed in [England and Wales](/England_and_Wales) on 1 July 1827 and in [India](/India) on 1 March 1829. It amended the Hue and Cry Act 1584 and was repealed by the [Criminal Statutes Repeal Act 1827](/Criminal_Statutes_Repeal_Act_1827) in England and Wales and by the [Criminal Law (India) Act 1828](/Criminal_Law_(India)_Act_1828) in India. It is related to the [Statute of Winchester](/Statute_of_Winchester) and the [Hue and Cry Act 1734](/Hue_and_Cry_Act_1734).

### Statute of Winchester

By the [Statute of Winchester](/Statute_of_Winchester) of 1285 ([13 Edw. 1. St. 2](/13_Edw._1._St._2). c. 4), it was provided that anyone, either a [constable](/Constable) or a private citizen, who witnessed a crime shall make hue and cry, and that the hue and cry must be kept up against the fleeing criminal from [town](/Town) to town and from [county](/County) to county, until the felon is apprehended and delivered to the [sheriff](/Sheriff). All able-bodied men between the ages of fifteen and sixty, upon hearing the shouts, were obliged to assist in the pursuit of the criminal, which makes it comparable to the [posse comitatus](/Posse_comitatus_(common_law)). It was moreover provided that "the whole [hundred](/Hundred_(division)) ... shall be answerable" for the [theft](/Theft) or [robbery](/Robbery) committed, in effect a form of [collective punishment](/Collective_punishment). Those who raised a hue and cry falsely were themselves guilty of a crime.

The hue and cry was utilized in medieval European towns and villages as a means of community policing. It was a system that relied on the collective responsibility of the community to maintain law and order. The oath of office for [constables](/Constables_in_the_United_States) in the [United States](/United_States) state of [Tennessee](/Tennessee) specifically mentions that it is the duty of the constable to sound the hue and cry.

## Etymology

The term "hue and cry" has an interesting etymology. It is possible that the term is an Anglicisation via [Anglo-French](/Anglo-Norman_language) of the [Latin](/Latin) hutesium et clamor, meaning "a horn and shouting." Other sources indicate that it has always been a somewhat redundant phrase meaning an outcry and cry, though such "redundancy" is a feature of the [legal doublet](/Legal_doublet). "Hue" appears to come from the [Old French](/Old_French) huer, which means "to shout," and "cry" from Old French crier ("to cry").

## Cultural References

The concept of hue and cry has permeated various aspects of culture and media. From the late 18th century until 1839, Hue and Cry was a principal or variant title for the weekly newspaper, containing details of crimes and wanted people, that afterwards became better known as the [Police Gazette](/Police_Gazette_(Great_Britain_and_Ireland)). Additionally, [Hue and Cry](/Hue_and_Cry_(film)) is a 1947 British film, which culminates in a call made to local children over the radio to join in the hunt to apprehend the villains.

